[1] Skunk, canine, equine - West Virginia
Date: 27 Oct 2010
Source State Journal [edited]
<http://www.statejournal.com/story.cfm?func=viewstory&storyid=88406>


According to the Greenbrier County Health Department, a skunk that
tangled with a dog on a tie-out in Alderson tested positive for the
disease.

The results came back from the West Virginia State Hygienic laboratory
on 26 Oct 2010.

The Monroe County Health Department announced a horse from Lindside
also tested positive for rabies, also on 26 Oct 2010.

The owners of the horse said it appeared to be healthy only a few
hours before it died.

Animal owners are urged to make sure their pets are up to date on
their rabies vaccinations.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The article does not give us any information on the dog that was in
contact with the skunk. Without information, it is tempting to say
that perhaps the dog was vaccinated, but most states require even
vaccinated animals to receive a booster vaccine when having been in
contact with a rabid animal.

The article does not provide much information on the horse either.
Generally, there are some clinical signs. Otherwise, why does someone
test for rabies when this death could have been from colic or another
cause. - Mod.TG]

