[6] Bat, human exposure - Texas
Date: 31 Oct 2010
Source: HCN Online [edited]
<http://www.hcnonline.com/articles/2010/10/31/atascocita_observer/news/44rabies2.txt>


Two toddlers and a young woman were exposed to a possibly rabid bat in
the backyard of a family member's home in Atascocita South Saturday
afternoon, 30 Oct 2010.

According to the grandfather, his 2- and 3-year-old grandsons were
playing outside when the 20-year-old mother of one of the boys went to
investigate and discovered the children were playing with a live bat.
"The bat jumped up into my daughter's pants leg," the
father/grandfather said. "She shook it out, and it flew up into a palm
tree."

The children's grandfather, who works in the medical field and has a
nursing license, said his daughter and the 2 toddlers immediately went
to seek treatment at the emergency room at Memorial Hermann Northeast
Hospital.

"The doctor initially said they had nothing to worry about since he
couldn't find any bite marks," the father/grandfather said. "But I
insisted that all of them get started on the series of rabies shots."
[Given the fact that these were small children playing with a live bat
in the daylight, the likelihood of exposure seems like it would be
pretty high. Therefore, it is astonishing that the physician would not
suggest post exposure prophylaxis. Bat bite marks are often impossible
to detect, and the children may not have realized they were bitten or
gotten bat saliva in a small cut. - Mod.TG]

A call to the Harris County health department reinforced his decision
to insist on treatment. "They told me it was a good thing to get the
rabies shots," he said. "Anytime you see a bat on the ground,
especially in broad daylight, there's something wrong with it."

The father/grandfather said his daughter knew the 16-year-old Humble
teen who died from rabies in 2006 after he was bitten by a bat that
had found its way into his room while he was sleeping. The memory of
Jones, for whom treatment came too late, also prompted the insistence
on receiving the 5-part series of rabies shots, a painful procedure
administered in the buttocks.

This is the 2nd report of an encounter with a possibly rabid bat in
Atascocita in October 2010. Earlier this month [October 2010], a young
boy found a dead bat at the Lindsay Lyons sports complex. The bat
tested positive for rabies, and the boy is undergoing the rabies shot
series. So far, no symptoms of the disease are present in any of the
victims.

[Byline: Stefanie Thomas]

