[7] Skunk, canine - Alabama
Date: 28 Oct 2010
Source: Wicked Local.com [edited]
<http://www.wickedlocal.com/melrose/news/lifestyle/health/x1272815410/Rabid-skunk-found-in-Melrose>


The Melrose Health Department and Melrose Canine Control Officer Diane
Kurkjian, CVT, are informing Melrose residents that a skunk caught on
Arlington Street in Melrose on Monday 11 Oct 2010 has tested positive
for rabies. A dog, which was in contact with the skunk, is being
quarantined; there were no other known contacts with the rabid animal.

The Health Department and Officer Kurkjian remind residents about what
to watch for in dealing with wildlife. People should not approach any
wildlife, or unknown domestic animals, they encounter outside.

If an animal appears sick, call Melrose Canine Control at
781-979-4102. Signs of illness would include discharge from the nose,
mouth or eyes; lack of coordination; walking into things; or otherwise
appearing to have neurological problems. Just being out in the
daytime, by itself, is not a sign of rabies. If a wild animal does not
appear sick, it can simply be ignored or scared away.

Pet owners should review their pets' rabies vaccination status. Pets
are much more likely than humans to have direct contact with wildlife,
and cats are more at risk than dogs, since many of them are free
roaming. This increases the risk to humans.

Owners of cats should consider keeping them indoors. Many cats each
year are lost to predators or are hit by cars. Cats will live longer,
healthier lives as indoor pets. However, even indoor-only pets should
be vaccinated against rabies, in case of accidental exposure.

--
