[9] Canine, equine, human exposure - Michigan
Date: 1 Nov 2010
Source: Wayne Independent [edited]
<http://www.wayneindependent.com/news/x1111394283/Rabies-cases-reported-in-Lake-Ariel>


2 cases of rabies involving a dog and a miniature horse have been
confirmed in Lake Ariel.

Marlene Metzger, Humane Society Police Officer for the Dessin Animal
Shelter, says both animals were located within a mile-and-a-half of
each other on Avoy Road. The dog, a collie-mix, died 26 Oct 2010,
while the miniature horse died in September 2010.

Both cases involved human exposure, requiring the pet owners to
undergo medical treatment. "At this point, we don't want to create any
hysteria, but we do want people who are in the area to watch their
pets. Make sure they're not unattended. We also want to make sure that
people have their pets vaccinated," said Dr. Amy Platko, a
veterinarian at Cherry Ridge Veterinary Clinic.

Platko says all cats and dogs 3 months of age or older should be
vaccinated and that pet owners should ensure that their pet's
vaccinations are up-to-date. The vaccine is "99 percent protective,"
Platko said. "If you do see any abnormal wounds on your pets, you
should contact your vet because they can re-inoculate them just to
give them added protection."

Platko says the collie was originally brought in for care because it
was limping and that it was "acting fine" at the time of the
evaluation. But within a week, it's condition had downgraded, with the
pet exhibiting abnormal, aggressive behavior before slipping into a
coma and dying. Rabid pets can appear in a stupor, exhibiting "less
responsive behaviors," Platko said, or they can become highly
aggressive.

Dr. Sandra Shaffer, Wallenpaupack Veterinary Clinic in Hawley, says
the miniature horse she was called to check on was storming its stall
door. "You'd open the stall door, and literally the horse would turn
around and charge at you ... which really struck me as an odd
behavior," Shaffer said. "It was also displaying abnormal neurologic
behavior. It was uncoordinated. It was making repetitive chewing
motions."

"When [people] think of rabies, they think of the classic rabid dog
that's snarling and drooling and maybe afraid of water. While large
animals can display those behaviors, rabies can look like anything in
large animals. ... This particular horse that we saw was screaming,"
Shaffer said. Shaffer said Pennsylvania has seen 4 case of rabies in
horses this year [2010] alone. [In actuality, the animals are not
afraid of water but unable to drink because of lack of muscular
control for swallowing. They cannot swallow their own saliva, and
hence the frequently observed drooling. The animals are often thirsty
but unable to drink. - Mod.TG]

"I think a lot of people are under the impression that rabies is a
small animal disease. We vaccinate dogs and cats routinely, but
oftentimes people are unaware that cows and horses and other livestock
are also susceptible," Shaffer said. Annual rabies vaccinations for
large animals run right around USD 25.

"I just think my main message is rabies is a disease that can affect
any mammal. And I think if you have large animals, it's just as
important to vaccinate them as it is your dog or cat," Shaffer said.

Dessin Animal Shelter Manager Sue Frisch says, "If you love your
animals, have them vaccinated. The animals that carry rabies are rural
as well as urban, so they're in town as well as out in the farmlands,
game lands and everywhere else."

[Byline: Tammy Compton]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[This article is good about pointing out that rabies can affect any
mammal. If you have pets, even if that pet is a horse or a cow or a
goat or a sheep, it is important to get it vaccinated against rabies.
That is for their protection and your protection. - Mod.TG]

