[10] Bat, unknown human exposure - California
Date: 2 Nov 2010
Source: New University [edited]
<http://www.newuniversity.org/2010/11/news/rabid-bats-are-just-as-scary-as-they-sound/>


A rabid bat was discovered near a middle school in San Juan
Capistrano, a city 20 miles south of Irvine. The bat, which was found
alive, was discovered on Wednesday, 20 Oct 2010. It is unknown whether
or not the bat transferred its infection to any other animals [or
humans], however no cases of rabies in humans or any mammal (other
than bats), have been reported in Orange County for many years.

Ryan Drabnk, the director of the Orange County Animal Care Center
explained the concern about rabies is still high. "Orange County is
still considered a rabies area," Drabnk said. "There have been 16
other cases of rabies, all concerning bats, in Orange County since the
beginning of this year [2010]."

Areas in Orange County where rabid bats have been found include
Newport Beach, Orange, Anaheim and Irvine. While rabid bats are not
uncommon in Orange County, this year [2010], there have been
particularly large numbers of infected animals discovered. The Orange
County Health Department and the Irvine Department of Animal Control
have both issued press releases warning O.C. residents to be aware of
the increased risk of rabies.

Rabies, a virus that can affect all mammals, is transferred through
saliva, making bites from rabid animals particularly dangerous. Dr.
David Lyon, a professor at UCI who uses the rabies virus in his
research, stated that an infected animal will, in the 1st 1-3 days
after infection, seem "depressed, moribund and hyper-excitable," and
"will exhibit marked depression in activity."

When left untreated, rabies is almost always fatal, so getting medical
attention before the symptoms set in is very important. If rabies is
confirmed, the "post-exposure treatment" includes an injection of
human antibodies for the rabies virus and a series of 4 intramuscular
shots given over weeks. "The treatment is equal to any other series of
shots, for instance, the measles vaccine," said Dr. Hildy Meyers,
medical director of epidemiology for the Orange County Health Care
Agency. She further warned that the best way to avoid contracting
rabies is to avoid contacting wild animals.

If you are bitten by an animal believed to be rabid, thoroughly wash
out the bite, making sure to clean out any saliva in the wound, and
then immediately seek medical attention.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The continuing concern of pets lacking vaccination is prevalent in
this update. This update clearly points out the need to be vaccinating
your large animal pets. Vaccination for pets is effective and can save
owners from the loss of the pet in the event of exposure, but it is
also a safeguard for yourself if your pet is exposed.

If you believe you have been exposed, seek medical attention right
away. In the case of bats, even if you cannot find a bite wound, post
exposure prophylaxis may be in order. Once clinical signs are present
in humans, it is generally a fatal disease, so if you believe you have
been exposed, it is important to seek immediate medical care. - Mod.TG]
